ce:section.ce:para:
In our previous work, we demonstrated that the strong surface electron-withdrawing structure of the CO groups on the CDs contributed to their pure red emission. [25] The decreased main absorption band and the red emission are likely due to the surface chemical structural changes of the CDs after xenon lamp irradiation with 450 nm LP filter. XPS was carried out to investigate the chemical structures of the CDs and ir-CDs. The full survey of the XPS spectra revealed the presence of C, N, and O as shown in Fig. 3
                     a. The atomic content of C, N and O for CDs and ir-CDs changed from 59.9%, 15.5% and 24.6% to 61.1%, 13.6% and 25.3% respectively with little changes (Table 1
                     ). As shown in Fig. 3b–3d, the high-resolution C 1 s, N 1 s, and O 1 s XPS spectra respectively revealed the presence of CC/C  C (284.8 eV), C  N/C  O (286.8 eV), and CO/COO (288.6 eV) bonds; pyridinic N (399.8 eV) and pyrrolic N (400.7 eV) bonds; and CO (531.5 eV) and C  O/O  H (532.7 eV) bonds. After xenon lamp irradiation for 20 min (0.3 W cm−2, 450 nm LP filter), the pyridinic N and CO content in the CDs respectively decreased from 10.2% and 17.4% to 4.8% and 10.3%, while the pyrrolic N and C  O/O  H content increased from 5.3% and 7.2% to 8.8% and 15.0%. It can be inferred that the electron-withdrawing pyridinic N and CO groups on the CD surface were reduced to pyrrolic N and C–OH following xenon lamp irradiation.
